    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1862-09-19T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1862-09-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="312" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d312">
                <head>
                    <persName type="from">Mr. Seward</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr.
                                Dayton</persName>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 220.]</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <hi rend="italic"> Washington,</hi>
                        </placeName>
                        <date calendar="gregorian" when="1862-09-19">
                            <hi rend="italic">September</hi> 19, 1862.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir:</hi> I have received your interesting despatch
                            of September 3, (No. 189.) A republican education has, indeed, made all
                            of us politicians; but it must now be confessed that the same education
                            has also made us soldiers, as cheerful to fight the battles of our
                            country as we are bold to discuss its affairs. I think no nation has
                            ever exhibited such voluntary armies.</p>
                <p>I am, sir, your obedient servant,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>WILLIAM H. SEWARD.</signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">William L. Dayton</hi>, Esq., <hi rend="italic">&amp;c., &amp;c., &amp;c.</hi>
                    </p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
        </body>
